# ============================================================================
# SECTION 1: CLAUDE API KEY (ANTHROPIC)
# ============================================================================
#
# WHAT IS THIS?
# Your API key to use Claude AI for compliance scoring
#
# WHERE TO GET IT:
# 1. Go to: https://console.anthropic.com/
# 2. Sign up or log in
# 3. Click "API Keys" in left sidebar
# 4. Click "Create Key"
# 5. Copy the entire key (it will start with "sk-ant-")
#
# FORMAT:
# - Must start with: sk-ant-
# - Total length: ~45-50 characters
# - Contains letters and numbers
#
# EXAMPLE (DO NOT USE - THIS IS FAKE):
# sk-ant-1234567890abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz
#
# YOUR KEY HERE:
#

ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-YOUR_ACTUAL_KEY_HERE


# ============================================================================
# SECTION 2: GOOGLE VISION API KEY - CHOOSE ONE APPROACH
# ============================================================================
#
# You have 3 options. Pick ONE based on your use case:


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# OPTION A: JSON FILE PATH (For Local Development Only)
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# WHAT IS THIS?
# Direct path to your Google service account JSON file
#
# WHERE TO GET THE JSON FILE:
# 1. Go to: https://console.cloud.google.com/
# 2. Create new project (name: "kyc-apexon" or similar)
# 3. Search for "Cloud Vision API" and enable it
# 4. Go to "APIs & Services" → "Credentials"
# 5. Click "Create Credentials" → "Service Account"
# 6. Fill in details:
#    - Service account name: kyc-service
#    - Grant role: Editor (or Viewer, but Editor is safer)
# 7. Go to the service account you just created
# 8. Click "Keys" tab
# 9. Click "Add Key" → "Create new key"
# 10. Choose "JSON" format
# 11. Click "Create" (downloads automatically)
#
# WHAT YOU'LL GET:
# A JSON file that looks like:
# {
#   "type": "service_account",
#   "project_id": "your-project-123456",
#   "private_key_id": "abc123...",
#   "private_key": "-----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----\n...\n-----END PRIVATE KEY-----\n",
#   ... more fields ...
# }
#
# HOW TO USE:
# 1. Save the JSON file somewhere on your computer
#    Example: C:\Users\luisr\Apexon\Credentials\google-vision-key.json
# 2. Copy the FULL PATH (not the contents!)
# 3. Paste it below as the value (uncomment the line)
#
# EXAMPLE (DO NOT USE - THIS IS FAKE PATH):
# GOOGLE_VISION_JSON_PATH=C:\Users\luisr\Apexon\Credentials\google-vision-key.json
#
# OR for Mac/Linux:
# GOOGLE_VISION_JSON_PATH=/Users/luisr/kyc-apexon/service-account.json
#
# FOR LOCAL TESTING, UNCOMMENT AND USE:
#

# GOOGLE_VISION_JSON_PATH=/full/path/to/your/service-account.json


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# OPTION B: BASE64 ENCODED JSON (For Vercel Cloud Deployment - RECOMMENDED)
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# WHAT IS THIS?
# Your JSON file converted to Base64 format (one long string)
#
# WHY USE THIS?
# Vercel can't easily store file paths. Base64 is a text string you can paste
# directly into Vercel environment variables.
#
# HOW TO CONVERT YOUR JSON TO BASE64:
#
# METHOD 1: Windows PowerShell (EASIEST)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────
# 1. Open PowerShell
# 2. Go to folder with your JSON file
# 3. Run this command:
#
#    $json = Get-Content "service-account.json" -Raw
#    $bytes = [System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes($json)
#    $base64 = [Convert]::ToBase64String($bytes)
#    $base64 | Set-Clipboard
#
# 4. Your base64 string is now copied to clipboard
# 5. Paste it below (it will be a very long string)
#
# METHOD 2: Mac/Linux Terminal
# ─────────────────────────────
# 1. Open terminal
# 2. Go to folder with your JSON file
# 3. Run:
#
#    cat service-account.json | base64
#
# 4. Copy the output
# 5. Paste it below
#
# METHOD 3: Online Tool (If above don't work)
# ────────────────────────────────────────────
# 1. Go to: https://www.base64encode.org/
# 2. Upload your service-account.json file
# 3. Click "Encode"
# 4. Copy the result
# 5. Paste below
#
# WHAT IT LOOKS LIKE:
# Very long string of letters, numbers, +, /, = signs
# Example start: eyJ0eXBlIjogInNlcnZpY2VfYWNjb3VudCIsICJwcm9qZWN0X2lkIjo...
# Example end: ...SIn0=
#
# IMPORTANT:
# - NO line breaks in the middle (must be ONE continuous line)
# - If copying from terminal, remove any newlines
# - Should be 2000-3000 characters long
#
# FOR VERCEL CLOUD DEPLOYMENT, UNCOMMENT AND USE:
#

# GOOGLE_VISION_JSON_BASE64=eyJ0eXBlIjogInNlcnZpY2VfYWNjb3VudCIsICJwcm9qZWN0X2lkIjogIm15LXByb2plY3QtMTIzNDU2Iiwg...


# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# OPTION C: DIRECT JSON STRING (Alternative, Less Common)
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# WHAT IS THIS?
# The entire JSON file contents on a single line
#
# NOT RECOMMENDED because:
# - Hard to read
# - Easy to make mistakes
# - Difficult to debug
#
# ONLY USE IF:
# - Options A and B don't work
# - You absolutely need it for some reason
#
# HOW TO DO IT:
# 1. Open your service-account.json file in a text editor
# 2. Remove all line breaks (make it one line)
# 3. Paste below as a single line
#
# WILL LOOK LIKE:
# {"type": "service_account", "project_id": "my-project-123456", ...entire json on one line...}
#
# NOT RECOMMENDED - ONLY IF NEEDED:
#

# GOOGLE_VISION_JSON={"type": "service_account", "project_id": "my-project-123456", ...}


# ============================================================================
# SECTION 3: WHICH OPTION TO USE?
# ============================================================================
#
# FOR LOCAL DEVELOPMENT:
# → Use OPTION A (GOOGLE_VISION_JSON_PATH)
# → Easier to manage, can see the file
# → Points to your JSON file on your computer
#
# FOR VERCEL CLOUD DEPLOYMENT:
# → Use OPTION B (GOOGLE_VISION_JSON_BASE64)
# → Recommended by Vercel
# → Works with their environment variables
# → Most secure and clean
#
# NEVER USE:
# → Don't use multiple options at once
# → Pick ONE and uncomment only that one
# → Comment out all others with #


